1. both parties recognised the territory of the other;
2. there was to be an alliance and peace between Philip and the Athenians, with no time limit;
3. the peace and the alliance was to be binding to the allies of both parties;
4. the seas were to be kept safe i.e. neither party was to support pirates]

[That the story of Phaedra already existed]
 ΕΥ.  Πότερον δ’ οὐκ ὄντα λόγον τοῦτον περὶ τῆς Φαίδρας ξυνέθηκα;
  ΑΙ.  Μὰ Δί’, ἀλλ’ ὄντ’·

[That they will give counsel in accordance with the laws;
That they will give the best counsel to the polis/to the demos of the Athenians;
That they will not imprison any Athenian citizen who offers three sureties taxed in the same class as themselves, except any person found guilty of conspiring to betray the city or to overthrow the democracy, or any tax-farmer or his surety or collector being in default;
That they will neither exile, nor imprison, nor put to death anybody without trial;
That if someone coins money of silver in the poleis and does not use Athenian coins or weights or measures, but uses foreign coins and weights and measures, they shall impeach him according to the former decree proposed by Clearchus (added ca.448);
That they are not less than thirty years old;
That they will not put to the vote anything contrary to the laws]

remarks:
Aeschines is following the flawed historical narrative from Andocides, On the Peace with the Spartans, 3-5. (See oath id 2383). It is typical of Andocides' historical inaccuracy. 
Aeschines and Andocides both state Miltiades, the son of Cimon negotiated a fifty year treaty with the Spartans, by which the Athenians abided for thirteen years. 
This, however, was not the case. It was Cimon the son of Miltiades who was ostracised (461) and negotiated a peace with the Spartans (451/0).  
This truce actually lasted for five years.  
Both Aeschines and Andocides state that the Athenians gained the following benefits from the peace: 
1. they fortified the Piraeus; 
2. they built the northern Long Wall; 
3. they built one hundred triremes to replace the old ones; 
4. they established a force of three hundred horsemen; 
5. they purchased the three hundred Scythian archers. 
See also oath id 1542.

